## Speeding up VPC creation

I used an alternative way to set up an Amazon VPC! This time, I VPC and More

A VPC resource map is one that helps understand how different components in my setup are connected and interact with each other. This makes it easier to design, manage, and troubleshoot my architecture because I can see everything at a glance, rather than sifting through lists and configurations

My new VPC has a CIDR block of 10.0.0.0./16 It is possible for my new VPC to have the same IPv4 CIDR block as my existing VPC because VPCs are isolated networks within AWS, meaning they don’t interact with each other unless you explicitly set up connectivity between them.

On the other hand, subnets within a VPC are part of the same network and can directly communicate with each other. Overlapping CIDR blocks within a VPC would create IP address conflicts, making it impossible to route traffic correctly. So, subnets need unique CIDR blocks to ensure smooth internal networking.

![Image](http://nextwork.ai/soothed_gold_swift_blueberry/uploads/aws-networks-ec2_1cbb1b88)

